: 1532}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:885"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CCK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9930832386016846, "span": {"begin": 1553, "end": 1556}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:3847"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "soybean", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7398119568824768, "span": {"begin": 1667, "end": 1674}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5644"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "trypsin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.650155782699585, "span": {"begin": 1675, "end": 1682}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5644"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "trypsin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9650422930717468, "span": {"begin": 1702, "end": 1709}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "soya", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9022246599197388, "span": {"begin": 1829, "end": 1833}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "soya", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.797312319278717, "span": {"begin": 1867, "end": 1871}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5644"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "trypsin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9873030781745911, "span": {"begin": 1916, "end": 1923}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:885"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CCK", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9951463341712952, "span": {"begin": 1956, "end": 1959}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "soya", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7463300824165344, "span": {"begin": 2029, "end": 2033}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "soya", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.742312490940094, "span": {"begin": 2097, "end": 2101}}], "text": "No study has shown a relationship between the trypsin inhibitor dose or degree of trypsin activity and the luminal concentration of MP. Trypsin inhibitor dosing and CCK levels &nbsp;are presented here. Considering that MP directly stimulates CCK release from I cells in the small intestine in rodents, increased plasma CCK levels induced by TIs seems to be appropriate as a surrogate of increased luminal MP levels.  The plasma CCK8 level in rats after 18-hour fasting was 0.31 &plusmn; 0.05 pM (mean &plusmn; SE) and increased to 6.2 &plusmn; 1.8 pM 7.5 minutes after feeding and increased to 10.3 &plusmn; 1.8 pM 15 minutes after intragastric instillation of a soybean trypsin inhibitor [Liddle RA et al, 1984].  Immediately after oral feeding of camostat at 400 mg/kg in rats, the plasma CCK level increased 10-fold above that in controls, reached a maximum after 90 min, remained elevated for more than 6 h, and then returned to control levels 24 h after administration of camostat [Goke B et al, 1986].  Plasma concentrations of CCK were measured after administration of a single dose of 200 mg/kg camostat by gavage or 2.5 &mu;g/kg CCK8 by subcutaneous administration to rats. The maximum CCK level, 9.6 &plusmn; 2.7 pM, was reached at 30 min after administration of CCK8, and that of 4.9 &plusmn; 1.2 pM over the time period of 15&ndash;240 min per animal with basal CCK concentration of about 2.5 pM [Douglas BR et al, 1989].  In isolated vascularly perfused rat duodenum/jejunum 30-min of infusion of trypsin with ovalbumin hydrolysate reduced CCK release by approximately 60% of that induced by the peptone alone. This effect was reversed by co-infusion of soybean trypsin inhibitor with the trypsin&ndash;peptone mixture [Cuber JC et al, 1990].  Eleven healthy volunteers consumed one of two meals: one containing raw soya flour and the other heat-treated soya flour. The two flours contained 34 and 3 mg trypsin/g flour, respectively. The peak CCK response was 16.8 &plusmn; 8.1 (mean &plusmn; SE) pmol/l for the raw soya flour diet versus 4.9 &plusmn; 2.8 pmol/l for the heat-treated soya flour diet (P &lt; 0.05) [Calam J et al, 1987].", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:24:27 +0000 2026"}